<br>
I'm still on the fence about ITER.  Although I think it is very important to study burning fusion plasmas, there are also many other things that need to be studied as well.  The main issue is the fusion program only has so much money.  Unless this is expanded to account for ITER, many smaller experiments just as valuable (albeit not as grandiose) will likely be cut back or eliminated all together.  This will, in the long run, hurt the effort because the issues will not go away and in the future the experiments will just have to be rebuilt at greater cost. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1079<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/2/03 1:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=135.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Canada wants fusion plant</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>We were stupid to ever pull out of it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually it seems like there might a light on the horizon.  According to this <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.spacedaily.com/news/energy-tech-03b.html">article</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> Bush has decided to join the ITER project.  This is the only source I've seen that hints at the USA being involved with ITER so maybe Bush changed his mind or Congress decided it wasn't to be.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm still on the fence about ITER. Although I think it is very important to study burning fusion plasmas, there are also many other things that need to be studied as well. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I've also questioned whether we should be putting all of our eggs in one basket and just studying one possible method for obtaining fusion at the expense of the others but the general consensus seems to be that ITER will lead to an actual functioning fusion plant near the end of its life cycle so I'm optimistic even though we know how predictions can go.  Apparently ITER will be the second largest international research project, which begs the question, which project is number one? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 3/2/03 1:50:21 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 138<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/2/03 12:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=135.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Canada wants fusion plant</span><hr size=1> Yes.  We are in ITER for sure, knowing lots of members of the fusion community, I can vouch for this.  Also, the consensus on whether or not we should put all our eggs in one basket with ITER is far from unanimous.  Although most people see ITER as a good thing, many people are very nervous about the possible cuts to other just as valuable programs.  Also, ITER will probably never be a power plant itself.  It's just another research project to study burning plasmas initially.  Of course, more will be done in the future, but that is its primary purpose. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 268<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/2/03 3:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=135.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Canada wants fusion plant</span><hr size=1> The National Ignition Facility at LLNL is still under construction, but should provide excellent data on inertial confinement. There are other methods out there being tested.<br>
