eir &quot;cool&quot; links page I think John Muir must be rolling in his grave.  I agree with Nucleaon, the whole article was nothing but the typical vague generalities and baseless fear mongering in typical anti-nuke style.  I know a number of environmentalists are anti-fission but pro-fusion.   Hmm, lets go bring up some highlights:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>ITER Canada’s slogan is “Cleaner energy for our planet”. This slogan is misleading for two reasons … ITER will not be clean, nor will it ever provide any useful energy.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well its working toward that goal, duh.  Anybody can look up the facts on ITER and realize it's experimental.  The luddites must be given themselves a pat on the back for discovering this deeply hidden conspiracy that the reactor won't be connected to the grid.  Congratulations on your shrewd investigation skills!  It's amazing how people try to twist words all out of proportion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>For environmental and economic reasons, the world depends increasingly on renewable energy, and this is where applied energy research funds should be directed, not to fusion.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The classic false dichotomy ploy, it's either one or the other.  Renewable energy research is getting plenty of funding, no need to hyperventilate.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Energy efficiency, conservation and renewable energy are the key to a sustainable energy future. They can easily solve problems such as climate change and nuclear reactor accidents Clean renewable energy technologies are proven and available now, unlike fusion energy, which is an expensive and hazardous high-tech fantasy more than 50 years away.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yeah, lets be short sighted and intentionally shut down research that may solve energy problems for future generations. I'm sure they'll thank us for it, and no doubt manufacturing millions upon millions of windmills will be the most environmentally friendly thing we ever did not to mention littering every square meter of the planet with solar cell farms, damming up every river in existence, and plowing up even more precious Earth or reducing farmland that could be producing food to grow ungodly amounts of low efficiency biomass.  Fusion power would be more compact and take up less acreage and as a result would be very environmentally friendly.  I'd rather deal with a few radioactive ceramic and metal pieces that are only a few dozen meters in diameter than to mess with the mining and chemical nightmares of manufacturing all of the equipment they'd need to take advantage of their renewables.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Fusion reactors require large amounts of tritium for fuel -- tritium is a radioactive form of hydrogen that can cause cancer and birth defects<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I had no idea tritium was the only fuel that could be used in a nuclear fusion reactor,  I guess they accidently forgot to mention much safer fuels like 3He in their fair and unbiased report.  It was also nice of them not to tell us that fusion reactors can't melt down and half a dozen other things that make them much more safer than fission reactors.  But reading the report you'd think that fusion was just as dangerous, if not more so, than fission (as though fission is something we should lose sleep over in the first place.) <br>
